This paper deals with image quality assessment, which is a topic closely related to computer vision. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also employs a sparse representation-based approach, which involves learning the inherent structures of the reference image as a set of basis vectors. This approach is related to machine learning and neural networks, which are covered in cs.MM (Machine Learning) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-categories. The paper also involves comparing the structures of the reference and the distorted images, which can be seen as an information theory problem, covered in cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a new metric for image quality assessment, which can be seen as a statistical problem, covered in cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category.
